A historic conclave at the Vatican is underway to elect a new pope for the troubled church.
The chosen pontiff, selected by divine will, will lead 1.1 billion Roman Catholics into a new era.
Cardinals face a crucial decision between an older transitional figure or a younger, dynamic pastor to succeed John Paul II.
Cardinal Joseph Ratzinger, a frontrunner, led the procession to the chapel, emphasizing the importance of upholding church doctrine.
Despite the anticipation, the first ballot did not yield a successor, leaving the faithful awaiting the white smoke that signals the election of a new pope.
